node.text: Being a millionaire may be more common than you think. About 20 million people in the U.S. have enough assets to fit the definition, according to a 2020 study by Credit Suisse. Chris Hogan, author of the book “Everyday Millionaires,” surveyed more than 10,000 of those wealthy individuals to figure out their secret to success. Having a particular mindset almost universally contributed to millionaires’ success, Hogan said. He found that around 97% of millionaires surveyed believed they were in control of their own destiny. That is much higher than the 55% of the general population Hogan found to hold the same opinion. Check out this video to see the other four beliefs and practices that more than 90% of millionaires apply to their money.

node.title: More than 90% of millionaires used these five tools to build wealth

node.text: Americans are funding their retirement accounts at record rates. But figuring out how much your monthly contributions will be worth in a few decades can be confusing. As a rule of thumb, most financial advisors suggest that you save 10% to 15% of your salary. But if your goal is to get to $1 million, the percentage you need to invest will vary drastically based on how old you are when you start. Here's how you can make it happen.

node.text: Investments in farmland are growing across the country as people, including the ultra-wealthy like Bill Gates, look for new ways to grow their money. In 2020, Gates made headlines for becoming the largest private farmland owner in the U.S. He had accumulated more than 269,000 acres of farmland across 18 states in less than a decade. His farmland grows onions, carrots and even the potatoes that are used to make McDonald’s french fries. How is he making money off of farmland in the U.S.? Watch the video to find out.

node.title: Why the ultra-wealthy like Bill Gates are investing in U.S. farmland

node.text: Porsche is in the minds of many the ultimate sports car brand. Its cars – especially its legendary 911 – blend high performance with quality construction and even a solid reputation for dependability. But the brand that made its name with small nimble two-door sports cars ruffled feathers in the automotive world when it tried its hand at a four-door sport utility vehicle, the Cayenne. Today, SUVs make up a huge chunk of Porsche’s sales. The brand is now entering the race toward electrification – but this time the innovator is playing catch-up to others.

node.title: How Porsche went from sports cars to SUVs ... and EVs

node.text: It’s taken over two years, but these days Jeremy Mateo is finally feeling at home. Mateo, 27, is a real estate broker in Honolulu, Hawaii, and bought his first condo on Oahu island right before the coronavirus pandemic in March 2020. Over the course of a year he saved $60,000 for a down payment and worked toward his goal of buying his “dream home.” Then he spent another year renovating and furnishing his place. The last of his furniture arrived in spring 2021, finally closing the chapter on his homebuying journey. Here’s how Mateo bought his one-bedroom condo for $560,000. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.text:
“Our senior leaders are all sending a clear message: Take the time to unwind, destress and spend time with your loved ones. Do not work.” ⁠
⁠
Sportswear giant Nike has given its head office employees the week off, as the latest company to offer workers vacation in order to support their mental health in the wake of the coronavirus pandemic. ⁠
⁠
Nike isn't the only company to make a move like this, though. Read about the other companies that have given their workers time off to prevent burnout at the link in bio. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 31, 2021. May be an image of money and text that says 'Cuba's central bank now recognizes cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin CNBC 20011000 B 011011'.

node.text:
Cuba will now recognize and regulate cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin, citing “reasons of socioeconomic interest.”⁠
⁠
Resolution 215, which was published last week, says the central bank will set new rules for how to deal with digital currencies. Commercial providers of related services will now need a license from the central bank to continue operations.⁠
⁠
Read about why "it’s historic that they are embracing it,” at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 30, 2021. May be an image of monument, sky and text that says 'EU set to recommend reinstating restrictions on U.S. travelers CNBC'.

node.text:
Well, it was fun while it lasted.⁠
⁠
The European Union is reportedly planning to reinstate travel restrictions on U.S. visitors that were lifted as recently as June, according to multiple media reports. The planned move would come amid a Covid-19 surge fueled by the delta variant and a lack of reciprocity from American officials who have not lifted the U.S. entry ban on EU citizens earlier this year.⁠
⁠
Find out what this could mean for Americans traveling to the bloc’s 27 member nations at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 30, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, eyeglasses and text that says 'iPhone 13 will likely support calls and messages via satellites directly, top Apple analyst says CNBC'.

node.text:
New for subscribers: Apple is “optimistic about the trend of satellite communications” and “will likely” include the ability to connect to extraterrestrial networks in its coming iPhone 13, TFI Securities analyst Ming-Chi Kuo predicted in a note to investors on Sunday.⁠
⁠
“If Apple enables the relevant software functions, iPhone 13 users can call and send messages via satellite when not within 4G/5G coverage,” Kuo wrote.⁠
⁠
What could this mean for iPhone users? Find out at the link in bio. (Check out CNBC Pro for 7 days for free!)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 30, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'As Warren Buffett turns 91, the legendary investor prepares Berkshire Hathaway for a new economy FOXI TOAESY FOX FOX! SINECS CNBC'.

node.text:
Happy birthday, Warren Buffett. 🎉⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The Oracle of Omaha, who turned 91 years old Monday, is taking steps to make sure that Berkshire Hathaway — and his eventual successor — will be better-positioned to benefit from a technology-driven economy.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The conglomerate’s operating business is a patchwork of companies focused on the traditional backbone of the economy, from railroads, to batteries, insurance, home furnishing and retail. Because of the old economy orientation, Berkshire has missed out on the explosive growth seen in the Amazons of the world over the years. But the Buffett is showing his openness to investments that stray from Berkshire’s old economy core to adapt to the new world.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Details on how Berkshire is adapting at the link in bio.

node.text: Hurricane Ida made landfall in Louisiana on Sunday as a Category 4 storm with winds of 150 miles per hour, one of the strongest storms to hit the region since Hurricane Katrina. Ida, which has since been downgraded to a tropical storm, has left more than 1 million people in the area without power.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 30, 2021. May be an image of standing, screen and text that says 'PayPal is exploring a stock-trading platform for its u.S. customers 8:5 তর PAYPAL ÛY HOL DINGS INC P PayPal 290. CNBC 288. 286. 284. 282. 280. 278.0'.

node.text:
PayPal is exploring a possible stock-trading platform.⁠
⁠
After rolling out the ability to trade cryptocurrencies last year, the payments giant has been exploring ways to let users trade individual stocks, according to two sources familiar with the plans, and public details around a new executive hire. PayPal’s move comes amid a retail trading renaissance. More than 10 million new individual investors have entered the market in the first half of this year, roughly matching last year’s record level, according to estimates from JMP Securities. ⁠
⁠
When could the trading service potentially roll out? Find out at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 30, 2021. May be an image of skyscraper, sky and text that says 'China's regulatory crackdown has wiped billions off tech stocks CNBC'.

node.text:
Chinese authorities have introduced a slew of legislation in the past few months, largely aimed at the tech sector — a move that’s spooked investors and wiped out billions of dollars in value from the country’s internet giants. 😳⁠
⁠
Regulators have introduced anti-monopoly legislation focused on the so-called “platform economy” which broadly refers to internet companies operating a variety of services from e-commerce to food delivery. Regulations have also aimed at bolstering critical data security and protection laws. As a result, high-profile technology companies have faced investigations and punishments.⁠
⁠
But with visibility increasing on the requirements of companies, is now the time for investors to jump into Chinese tech stocks? Link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 29, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Alphabet's drones delivered 10,000 cups of coffee and 1,200 roast chickens in the last year A1404 Wing Wilgra CNBC'.

node.text:
Delivery by drone. :eyes:⁠
⁠
Alphabet’s drone company Wing delivered 10,000 cups of coffee, 1,700 snack packs and 1,200 roast chickens to customers in Logan, Australia, over the last year, the company said Wednesday.⁠
⁠
Wing was initially launched in 2019 in Australia, following a series of drone tests that began in 2014. The service, which was initially part of Alphabet’s experimental research division, allows users to order items such as food through a mobile app and is fast approaching 100,000 deliveries since its launch.⁠
⁠
Find out other companies that  are working on their own drone delivery at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 29, 2021. May be an image of 2 people, people standing and text that says 'Child tax credit lifted 3 million kids from poverty in July T CNBC'.

node.text:
The first installment of the child tax credit lifted 3 million kids out of poverty in July, according to a Columbia University study.⁠
⁠
That reduction represented a 25% cut in the monthly child poverty rate, to 11.9% from 15.8%, according to the analysis published Friday.⁠
⁠
“This is huge for low-income families,” Zachary Parolin, a researcher at the university’s Center on Poverty and Social Policy and a report co-author, said of recent changes to the child tax credit.⁠
⁠
More details on why the "potential for the benefit is huge" at the link in bio.⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 29, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, outdoors and text that says 'This universal basic income experiment is helping the homeless get off the streets CNBC'.

node.text:
More than six years ago, Kevin F. Adler walked the streets of his San Francisco neighborhood with an unusual purpose: He wanted to get to know its homeless residents.⁠
⁠
During that time, he met a man named Jeffrey, who had been a missing person for 12 years. After posting on social media, Adler was able to reconnect Jeffrey with his family, who had not seen him in more than 20 years. ⁠
⁠
The experience inspired Adler, whose own uncle was homeless for 30 years, to create a program called Miracle Messages to help reunite other unhoused individuals with their loved ones. The program has since raised money to pilot a universal basic income project for the homeless, distributing payments of $500 per month to 14 unhoused individuals.⁠
⁠
Read about how one man described the program as a “lifesaving experience,” at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 29, 2021. May be an image of 5 people and text that says 'Warren Buffett says these businesses do the best during periods of high inflation CNBC'.

node.text:
From used cars to gas to groceries, inflation continues to raise the price of goods in the U.S.⁠
⁠
But when it comes to investing during a period of high inflation, Berkshire Hathaway CEO Warren Buffett says there are some businesses that are more likely to succeed than others.⁠
⁠
When asked which of his company's holdings were best poised to thrive during a period of high inflation. Buffett's response: The best business to own is one that doesn't require continuous reinvestment because it becomes more and more expensive as the value of a dollar drops.⁠
⁠
What kind of companies does Buffett personally like to invest in? Link in bio. (With @CNBCMakeIt)
